            <p>Chicago&#44; Sep. 16&#44; 1879.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. and dear friend.<lb/></p>
            <p>Being<lb/> unfortunately detained in this<lb/> city by business over the Hol&#45;<lb/>idays&#44; my thoughts of you<lb/> now are as of old&#8212;the<lb/> brightest and most cheering<lb/> of my days&#8212;and I am<lb/> grateful to the Supreme for<lb/> permitting me to greet you<lb/> again as in former years<lb/> with a very&#44; <hi rend="underline">very</hi> &#34;Happy<lb/> New Year&#44;&#34;¬ùcoupled with<lb/> the sincere prayer that<lb/> the Almighty will spare<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>you for many years of<lb/> usefulness and pleasure&#44;<lb/> and that your affectionate<lb/> children will enjoy the<lb/> like blessings.<lb/></p>
            <p>Permit me&#44; my dear<lb/> sir&#44; through you to thank<lb/> Miss Nina for her polite<lb/> invitations to my daught&#45;<lb/>ers to visit her&#44; and which&#44;<lb/> I learn from them&#44; they<lb/> regret so much not<lb/> being able to avail of.<lb/></p>
            <p>With regards&#44; I am&#44;<lb/>
                Rev. S. Morais Pha	A. S. Solomons<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
